<!-- ABOUT LANDSLIDE -->
<article class="content-card">
  <h2>About Landslides</h2>
  <p>
    Landslides are downward movements of rock, soil, or debris triggered by
    heavy rainfall, earthquakes, deforestation, or unstable slopes.
  </p>
  <p>
    They frequently occur in the Himalayan region, Northeastern states,
    Western Ghats, and along roads with steep slopes.
  </p>
</article>

<!-- CAUSES -->
<article class="content-card">
  <h2>Common Causes</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Continuous heavy rainfall.</li>
    <li>Earthquakes or tremors.</li>
    <li>Deforestation and loose soil.</li>
    <li>Road cutting and slope construction.</li>
    <li>Blocked drainage channels.</li>
  </ul>
</article>

<!-- WARNING SIGNS -->
<article class="content-card">
  <h2>Early Warning Signs</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Cracks forming on walls or the ground.</li>
    <li>Trees or poles tilting unnaturally.</li>
    <li>Flowing water becoming muddy suddenly.</li>
    <li>Sounds of rocks falling or trees cracking.</li>
    <li>Sudden rise in water levels downstream.</li>
  </ul>
</article>

<!-- PREPAREDNESS -->
<article class="content-card">
  <h2>Preparedness Before a Landslide</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Avoid construction on steep slopes.</li>
    <li>Plant trees to stabilize soil.</li>
    <li>Keep drains clear to avoid waterlogging.</li>
    <li>Identify safe zones away from slopes.</li>
    <li>Listen to IMD rainfall warnings.</li>
  </ul>
</article>

<!-- DO‚Äôs & DON'Ts -->
<article class="content-card">
  <h2>Do‚Äôs & Don‚Äôts</h2>

  <h3>‚úî Do‚Äôs</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Move to higher, stable ground immediately.</li>
    <li>Follow official advisories.</li>
    <li>Stay alert during and after heavy rainfall.</li>
    <li>Help clear drainage paths if safe.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>‚ùå Don‚Äôts</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Do NOT live near steep or freshly cut slopes.</li>
    <li>Do NOT drive during landslides.</li>
    <li>Do NOT cross riverbanks during heavy rain.</li>
    <li>Do NOT go near landslide-prone roads.</li>
  </ul>
</article>

